1
00:00:02,191 --> 00:00:04,291
Okay in <i>Avatar</i> when
they gave sex in Pandora

2
00:00:04,491 --> 00:00:07,160
they hook up their ponytails,
so we know their ponytails

3
00:00:07,360 --> 00:00:09,896
are like their junk.

4
00:00:10,096 --> 00:00:11,531
Yeah... so?

5
00:00:11,731 --> 00:00:13,700
So, when they ride horses
and fly on the birds,

6
00:00:13,900 --> 00:00:15,068
they also use their ponytails.

7
00:00:15,268 --> 00:00:16,269
What's your point?

8
00:00:16,469 --> 00:00:18,271
My point is, if I were a horse or a bird,

9
00:00:18,471 --> 00:00:21,751
I'd be very nervous
around James Cameron.

10
00:00:22,208 --> 00:00:24,711
It amazes me how you
constantly obsess

11
00:00:24,911 --> 00:00:26,179
over fictional details

12
00:00:26,379 --> 00:00:27,781
when there are more important things

13
00:00:27,981 --> 00:00:29,149
in the real world to worry about.

14
00:00:29,349 --> 00:00:33,586
For example, why wasn't William
Shatner in the new <i>Star Trek</i> movie?

15
00:00:33,786 --> 00:00:34,621
Hey, Sheldon.

16
00:00:34,821 --> 00:00:36,089
I was up in the administration office,

17
00:00:36,289 --> 00:00:37,457
and I happened to overhear

18
00:00:37,657 --> 00:00:38,792
the name of the winner

19
00:00:38,992 --> 00:00:41,161
of this year's Chancellor's
Award for Science.

20
00:00:41,361 --> 00:00:43,229
And you want to rub
my nose in the fact

21
00:00:43,429 --> 00:00:45,098
that my contributions are
being overlooked again?

22
00:00:45,298 --> 00:00:49,135
I am the William Shatner
of theoretical physics.

23
00:00:49,335 --> 00:00:50,203
All right, I'll play.

24
00:00:50,403 --> 00:00:51,805
What self-important, preening fraud

25
00:00:52,005 --> 00:00:53,373
are they honoring this year?

26
00:00:53,573 --> 00:00:57,093
Oh, I'm so glad you asked it like that.
You.

27
00:00:58,444 --> 00:00:59,979
- I won?
- You won.

28
00:01:00,179 --> 00:01:02,415
I won!

29
00:01:02,615 --> 00:01:04,217
This is astonishing.

30
00:01:04,417 --> 00:01:06,820
Not that I won the award--
no one deserves it more.

31
00:01:07,020 --> 00:01:08,388
Actually, I guess I misspoke.

32
00:01:08,588 --> 00:01:11,458
It's not astonishing;
more like inevitable.

33
00:01:11,658 --> 00:01:12,826
I'm not sure what to do first.

34
00:01:13,026 --> 00:01:14,161
Maybe I should call my mother.

35
00:01:14,361 --> 00:01:16,296
Wait! I know-- I'm going
to conduct an interview

36
00:01:16,496 --> 00:01:18,976
with myself and post it online.

37
00:01:21,367 --> 00:01:22,902
Well, good for him.

38
00:01:23,102 --> 00:01:25,805
Yeah, the one thing
the William Shatner

39
00:01:26,005 --> 00:01:30,075
of theoretical physics
needed was an ego boost.

40
00:01:56,355 --> 00:01:59,235
(Dramatic movie music plays over TV)

41
00:02:13,472 --> 00:02:15,007
Didn't it look like that spear

42
00:02:15,207 --> 00:02:17,142
was going to go right
through your skull?

43
00:02:17,342 --> 00:02:18,842
No.

44
00:02:20,312 --> 00:02:21,914
Hey, you didn't want
a Slurpee at 7-Eleven,

45
00:02:22,114 --> 00:02:23,874
you don't get glasses.

46
00:02:24,816 --> 00:02:26,552
(Phone ringing)

47
00:02:26,752 --> 00:02:29,488
Oh, that will be another
congratulatory call for me.

48
00:02:29,688 --> 00:02:31,223
Uh, mute, please.

49
00:02:31,423 --> 00:02:34,303
Wait, wait. Hang on-- flaming arrow.

50
00:02:36,895 --> 00:02:38,163
Hello? (TV audio muted)

51
00:02:38,363 --> 00:02:41,563
Oh, Chancellor Morton,
how are you, sir?

52
00:02:43,135 --> 00:02:44,703
Yes, I was expecting your call.

53
00:02:44,903 --> 00:02:47,063
(Quietly): Three years ago.

54
00:02:47,572 --> 00:02:48,774
SHELDON: I see.

55
00:02:48,974 --> 00:02:51,777
Wait. What happens if I
choose not to give a speech?

56
00:02:51,977 --> 00:02:53,445
Uh-huh.

57
00:02:53,645 --> 00:02:56,925
And if I don't want to forfeit the award?

58
00:02:57,416 --> 00:03:00,152
Well, you've got that tied
up in a neat little bow.

59
00:03:00,352 --> 00:03:01,220
All right.

60
00:03:01,420 --> 00:03:02,821
Thank you.

61
00:03:03,021 --> 00:03:04,189
Problem.

62
00:03:04,389 --> 00:03:05,657
What?

63
00:03:05,857 --> 00:03:08,393
They expect me to give
a speech at the banquet.

64
00:03:08,593 --> 00:03:09,995
I can't give a speech.

65
00:03:10,195 --> 00:03:11,797
Well, no, you're mistaken.

66
00:03:11,997 --> 00:03:15,066
You give speeches all the time.

67
00:03:17,002 --> 00:03:20,072
What you can't do is shut up.

68
00:03:20,272 --> 00:03:21,840
KOOTHRAPPALI: Yeah,
before the movie,

69
00:03:22,040 --> 00:03:26,211
you did 20 minutes on why
guacamole turns brown.

70
00:03:26,411 --> 00:03:28,947
It turned brown while you were talking.

71
00:03:29,147 --> 00:03:31,884
I am perfectly comfortable
speaking to small groups.

72
00:03:32,084 --> 00:03:34,052
I cannot speak to large crowds.

73
00:03:34,252 --> 00:03:35,554
What, to you, is a large crowd?

74
00:03:35,754 --> 00:03:39,274
Any group big enough
to trample me to death.

75
00:03:39,591 --> 00:03:43,462
General rule of thumb is
36 adults or 70 children.

76
00:03:43,662 --> 00:03:46,498
Sheldon, congratulations.

77
00:03:46,698 --> 00:03:48,166
Brought you a cheesecake from work.

78
00:03:48,366 --> 00:03:49,668
You know, 'cause of your award,

79
00:03:49,868 --> 00:03:52,668
not because a busboy sneezed on it.

80
00:03:54,773 --> 00:03:57,342
I'm not accepting the award. Why not?

81
00:03:57,542 --> 00:04:00,146
Turns out the great Sheldon
Cooper has stage fright.

82
00:04:00,346 --> 00:04:01,847
That's no reason to back out.

83
00:04:02,047 --> 00:04:04,900
You know, I once got a pretty
big honor in high school,

84
00:04:05,100 --> 00:04:07,486
and I was terrified about
appearing in front of a big crowd,

85
00:04:07,686 --> 00:04:09,688
but I went through with it,
and you know what?

86
00:04:09,888 --> 00:04:12,441
The world looked pretty darn
good sitting on a haystack

87
00:04:12,641 --> 00:04:18,001
in the back of a Ford F-150 as a
member of the Corn Queen's Court.

88
00:04:19,064 --> 00:04:19,899
Thank you.

89
00:04:20,099 --> 00:04:21,233
Yeah, I'll bear that in mind

90
00:04:21,433 --> 00:04:25,593
if I'm ever nominated for
the Hillbilly Peace Prize.

91
00:04:26,738 --> 00:04:28,607
Sheldon, you're being ridiculous.

92
00:04:28,807 --> 00:04:31,207
Am I?
Let me tell you a story.

93
00:04:31,576 --> 00:04:34,696
Where's 70 children
when you need them?

94
00:04:35,047 --> 00:04:39,518
I was 14 and graduating summa
cum laude from college.

95
00:04:40,118 --> 00:04:43,255
"Summa cum laude" is Latin
for "with highest honors."

96
00:04:43,455 --> 00:04:45,057
I just love how you always skip

97
00:04:45,257 --> 00:04:47,926
over the part where no one asks.

98
00:04:48,126 --> 00:04:50,462
I was valedictorian and
expected to give an address.

99
00:04:50,662 --> 00:04:52,698
Even now, I can remember that moment

100
00:04:52,898 --> 00:04:55,901
when I walked up to the podium
and looked out at the crowd.

101
00:04:56,101 --> 00:04:57,903
There must have been
thousands of people.

102
00:04:58,103 --> 00:05:00,138
My heart started pounding in my chest.

103
00:05:00,338 --> 00:05:01,707
I began to hyperventilate.

104
00:05:01,907 --> 00:05:05,377
My vision became blurry,
and before I knew it...

105
00:05:05,577 --> 00:05:07,346
Oh, dear.

106
00:05:07,546 --> 00:05:08,947
Oh, my God.

107
00:05:09,147 --> 00:05:10,015
LEONARD: Sheldon?

108
00:05:10,215 --> 00:05:11,583
Sheldon, are you okay?

109
00:05:11,783 --> 00:05:13,784
Don't trample me.

110
00:05:16,087 --> 00:05:17,022
SHELDON: Come on, Mother.

111
00:05:17,222 --> 00:05:20,058
You know why I can't accept the award.

112
00:05:20,258 --> 00:05:24,262
With all due respect,
I don't think praying will help.

113
00:05:24,462 --> 00:05:28,367
No, I have not heard the song,
"Jesus, Take the Wheel."

114
00:05:28,567 --> 00:05:29,835
No, no, no, no, no, no, no.

115
00:05:30,035 --> 00:05:32,371
You don't need to start singing it.

116
00:05:32,571 --> 00:05:35,574
Yes, I'll buy it on the iTunes, Mother.

117
00:05:35,774 --> 00:05:37,374
Good-bye, Mother.

118
00:05:43,048 --> 00:05:45,017
Hello.

119
00:05:45,517 --> 00:05:47,152
Sit down. We want to talk to you.

120
00:05:47,352 --> 00:05:48,487
Am I in trouble?

121
00:05:48,687 --> 00:05:50,527
Did my mother call you?

122
00:05:50,789 --> 00:05:51,990
Just sit.

123
00:05:52,190 --> 00:05:54,861
LEONARD: We think we can
help you with your stage fright.

124
00:05:55,061 --> 00:05:57,295
Oh, I doubt that.

125
00:05:57,495 --> 00:06:02,401
I haven't figured out a way, and
I'm much smarter than all of you.

126
00:06:02,601 --> 00:06:05,804
Yes, but you're not smarter
than all of us put together.

127
00:06:06,004 --> 00:06:09,073
Oh, I'm sorry.
That is what I meant.

128
00:06:09,975 --> 00:06:13,278
Okay. Your problem is, you're
trying to do this all by yourself.

129
00:06:13,478 --> 00:06:15,313
We can help you.
We can be your team.

130
00:06:15,513 --> 00:06:18,793
Like, uh,
Professor Xavier and his X-Men.

131
00:06:21,920 --> 00:06:24,523
I do like the X-Men.

132
00:06:24,723 --> 00:06:26,758
Did I see <i>X-Men?</i>

133
00:06:26,958 --> 00:06:28,160
Yeah, we watched it last week.

134
00:06:28,360 --> 00:06:29,394
You said you liked it.

135
00:06:29,594 --> 00:06:32,394
Oh. I say a lot of things, sweetie.

136
00:06:33,665 --> 00:06:35,000
So, how about it, Sheldon?

137
00:06:35,200 --> 00:06:36,468
I don't know.

138
00:06:36,668 --> 00:06:39,971
If you're my X-Men,
what are your powers?

139
00:06:40,171 --> 00:06:43,809
Okay. Well, I am going to take
you shopping, get you a nice suit.

140
00:06:44,009 --> 00:06:45,210
Might give you more confidence.

141
00:06:45,410 --> 00:06:47,412
That's not exactly a
mutation that would get you

142
00:06:47,612 --> 00:06:50,348
into Xavier's School for Gifted
Youngsters, but go on.

143
00:06:50,548 --> 00:06:51,650
Leonard?

144
00:06:51,850 --> 00:06:53,719
I thought I could try to analyze you

145
00:06:53,919 --> 00:06:55,754
and get to the root of your anxiety.

146
00:06:55,954 --> 00:06:59,124
What qualifies you to attempt
to understand my mind?

147
00:06:59,324 --> 00:07:01,693
My mother is a highly
regarded psychiatrist,

148
00:07:01,893 --> 00:07:04,963
and I've been in therapy
ever since she accused me

149
00:07:05,163 --> 00:07:07,723
of breast-feeding codependently.

150
00:07:09,734 --> 00:07:11,837
Raj says he can teach you...

151
00:07:12,037 --> 00:07:13,839
What did you call it?

152
00:07:14,039 --> 00:07:17,479
I don't know-- some
Indian meditation crap.

153
00:07:18,843 --> 00:07:19,878
I see.

154
00:07:20,078 --> 00:07:21,847
Well, I assume, since the rest of you

155
00:07:22,047 --> 00:07:24,216
have set the bar so low, you're saving

156
00:07:24,416 --> 00:07:25,851
the most impressive
contribution for last.

157
00:07:26,051 --> 00:07:27,185
Go ahead, Howard.

158
00:07:27,385 --> 00:07:29,453
Dazzle me.

159
00:07:30,689 --> 00:07:33,409
My power is the ability to pretend

160
00:07:33,625 --> 00:07:37,705
like I give a damn about
your piddily-ass problems.

161
00:07:42,767 --> 00:07:45,602
And that's 24-seven, buddy.

162
00:07:46,805 --> 00:07:49,740
And I appreciate the pretense.

163
00:07:50,875 --> 00:07:53,678
So, what do you say, Sheldon?
Are we your X-Men?

164
00:07:53,878 --> 00:07:54,880
No.

165
00:07:55,080 --> 00:07:58,283
The X-Men were named for
the "X" in Charles Xavier.

166
00:07:58,483 --> 00:08:02,820
Since I am Sheldon Cooper,
you will be my C-Men.

167
00:08:07,826 --> 00:08:09,994
Oh, that's not a good name.

168
00:08:12,063 --> 00:08:14,499
(Indian music playing)

169
00:08:14,699 --> 00:08:16,101
Okay, Sheldon.

170
00:08:16,301 --> 00:08:17,803
I'm going to be leading you

171
00:08:18,003 --> 00:08:20,005
through a series of
meditation exercises.

172
00:08:20,205 --> 00:08:23,308
These methods come from
the ancient gurus of India

173
00:08:23,508 --> 00:08:26,788
and have helped me
overcome my own fears.

174
00:08:27,579 --> 00:08:30,514
And yet, you can't speak to women.

175
00:08:31,716 --> 00:08:33,819
True, but thanks to meditation,
I am able to stay

176
00:08:34,019 --> 00:08:37,619
in the same room with
them without urinating.

177
00:08:38,723 --> 00:08:41,993
Now... (clears throat) close your eyes.

178
00:08:42,193 --> 00:08:44,930
Okay, but don't punch me.

179
00:08:45,130 --> 00:08:46,298
What?

180
00:08:46,498 --> 00:08:48,567
When I was little,
my sister would say to me,

181
00:08:48,767 --> 00:08:50,469
"Close your eyes, you'll get a surprise,"

182
00:08:50,669 --> 00:08:52,270
and then she'd punch me.

183
00:08:52,470 --> 00:08:54,106
I'm not going to punch you.

184
00:08:54,306 --> 00:08:56,975
That's what my sister used to say.

185
00:08:57,175 --> 00:08:58,577
Do you want to do this or not?

186
00:08:58,777 --> 00:09:00,378
I'm sorry. Proceed.

187
00:09:00,578 --> 00:09:02,080
All right. (Clears throat)

188
00:09:02,280 --> 00:09:04,149
Imagine yourself in the one place

189
00:09:04,349 --> 00:09:05,917
you feel most at home.

190
00:09:06,117 --> 00:09:07,285
Where is that?

191
00:09:07,485 --> 00:09:10,421
Sim City.

192
00:09:11,823 --> 00:09:14,960
More specifically,
the Sim City I designed--

193
00:09:15,160 --> 00:09:17,028
Sheldonopolis.

194
00:09:17,228 --> 00:09:19,498
Okay, you're in Sheldonopolis.

195
00:09:19,698 --> 00:09:21,233
Where exactly?

196
00:09:21,433 --> 00:09:23,368
Sheldon Square? Sheldon Towers?

197
00:09:23,568 --> 00:09:27,038
Sheldon Stadium,
home of the Fighting Sheldons?

198
00:09:27,238 --> 00:09:28,540
Whatever you like.

199
00:09:28,740 --> 00:09:31,309
I thought this was supposed
to be a guided meditation.

200
00:09:31,509 --> 00:09:34,146
Fine. You're in Sheldon Square.

201
00:09:34,346 --> 00:09:35,347
Really? This time of year?

202
00:09:35,547 --> 00:09:36,748
It's a bit nippy.

203
00:09:36,948 --> 00:09:38,817
Then, put on a sweater.

204
00:09:39,017 --> 00:09:40,752
Suppose I could run downtown

205
00:09:40,952 --> 00:09:44,055
and pick up something at Shel-Mart.

206
00:09:44,255 --> 00:09:46,024
Yeah, whatever. Just go buy a sweater.

207
00:09:46,224 --> 00:09:48,360
You know, the nice thing
about Shel-Mart is I own it,

208
00:09:48,560 --> 00:09:50,796
so I get a 15% discount.

209
00:09:50,996 --> 00:09:52,497
You own the damn thing.

210
00:09:52,697 --> 00:09:54,466
Just take a freaking sweater!

211
00:09:54,666 --> 00:09:56,668
Look, I didn't turn a profit last quarter

212
00:09:56,868 --> 00:09:59,671
by taking product off
the shelves willy-nilly.

213
00:09:59,871 --> 00:10:02,440
All right.

214
00:10:02,640 --> 00:10:06,478
You've paid for a sweater,
and you're in Sheldon Square.

215
00:10:06,678 --> 00:10:09,046
(Clears throat) Hang on.

216
00:10:10,315 --> 00:10:13,275
It's a cardigan. I have to button it.

217
00:10:15,854 --> 00:10:17,055
Oh, no.

218
00:10:17,255 --> 00:10:18,223
What now?

219
00:10:18,423 --> 00:10:21,259
A Godzilla-like monster
is approaching the city.

220
00:10:21,459 --> 00:10:23,595
I have to get my people to safety.

221
00:10:23,795 --> 00:10:26,798
People of Sheldonopolis,
this is your mayor.

222
00:10:26,998 --> 00:10:28,066
Follow me.

223
00:10:28,266 --> 00:10:31,869
If the children can't run,
leave them behind.

224
00:10:33,471 --> 00:10:36,740
Oh, the simulated horror!

225
00:10:38,243 --> 00:10:39,843
(Door slamming)

226
00:10:45,650 --> 00:10:47,785
Raj?

227
00:10:49,054 --> 00:10:50,989
Just as I suspected.

228
00:10:51,189 --> 00:10:53,791
Meditation is nothing but hokum.

229
00:10:59,925 --> 00:11:01,460
I question your premise.

230
00:11:01,660 --> 00:11:03,695
How is a new suit going to prevent me

231
00:11:03,895 --> 00:11:05,998
from passing out in front of
a ballroom full of people?

232
00:11:06,198 --> 00:11:08,000
It'll give you confidence.

233
00:11:08,200 --> 00:11:09,701
You know, sometimes when
I'm feeling all stressed out

234
00:11:09,901 --> 00:11:12,004
about something,
I go out and buy a cute top

235
00:11:12,204 --> 00:11:15,440
or a fun skirt and I have a
whole new outlook on life.

236
00:11:15,640 --> 00:11:17,142
Don't you eventually realize

237
00:11:17,342 --> 00:11:18,977
you're just the same
stressed out person

238
00:11:19,177 --> 00:11:21,497
in a cute top or a fun skirt?

239
00:11:21,779 --> 00:11:24,448
Yeah, that's when I buy shoes.

240
00:11:25,016 --> 00:11:26,751
Now, let's see what we've got.

241
00:11:26,951 --> 00:11:27,919
Ooh!

242
00:11:28,119 --> 00:11:30,322
This is nice.

243
00:11:30,522 --> 00:11:33,225
It's only one color.

244
00:11:33,425 --> 00:11:34,593
Yeah, so?

245
00:11:34,793 --> 00:11:37,796
That's a lot of money for only one color.

246
00:11:37,996 --> 00:11:41,533
Fine. Why don't you pick out
what you like.

247
00:11:41,733 --> 00:11:44,069
Hmm.

248
00:11:44,569 --> 00:11:46,969
SHELDON: This is pretty sharp.

249
00:11:52,543 --> 00:11:55,478
No, you're wrong.

250
00:11:55,947 --> 00:11:57,716
This is great.

251
00:11:57,916 --> 00:12:01,218
I had a suit like this when I was six.

252
00:12:05,056 --> 00:12:07,536
Okay, I think we have a winner.

253
00:12:09,961 --> 00:12:11,596
Where the hell'd you find that?

254
00:12:11,796 --> 00:12:13,965
In the prom department.

255
00:12:14,165 --> 00:12:15,367
It's ridiculous.

256
00:12:15,567 --> 00:12:19,487
Says the former member
of the Corn Queen's Court.

257
00:12:20,405 --> 00:12:22,807
Please just try this one on.

258
00:12:23,007 --> 00:12:23,842
Okay.

